    <div class="card-grid">
      <div class="hbox hbox-head">
        <strong>The brain parenchyma is NOT pain-sensitive!</strong>
        Pain arises from: Circle of Willis · Proximal dural arteries (middle meningeal) · Dural venous sinuses · Meninges · Dura · First 3 cervical nerves (connected to trigeminal nucleus caudalis)
      </div>
      <div class="hbox hbox-info">
        <strong>Most Important Clinical Point:</strong>
        History ALONE can give the diagnosis in primary headache. No biomarkers exist. CT/MRI only rules OUT secondary causes.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="sub-title">Brain Mechanisms of Headache Pain</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-head">Mechanism</th><th class="th-head">Example</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Traction on Circle of Willis</td><td>Aneurysm, mass</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dilatation of intra/extracranial vessels</td><td><strong>Migraine</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Induced SPASM of vessels</td><td>Cervicogenic, Tension HA</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Inflammation of structures + meninges</td><td><strong>Meningitis</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Inflammation of blood vessels</td><td><strong>Arteritis</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Sustained contraction of neck/scalp muscles</td><td><strong>Tension HA</strong></td></tr>
          <tr><td>Changes in ICP (nasal, paranasal, orbits, teeth)</td><td>Tumor, sinusitis</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Direct pressure on nerve pain fibers</td><td>Neuralgia</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
