          <tr><td>Abstraction</td><td>2</td><td>tren–bisikleta (transportation) · timbangan–ruler (pangsukat). Score only ABSTRACT not literal answers.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Delayed Recall</td><td>5</td><td>Free recall of 5 words: mukha, asul, simbahan, rosas, seda (1pt each uncued)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Orientation</td><td>6</td><td>Date/Month/Year/Day/City/Place</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--mem)">Agnosia ⭐⭐</div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-mem">
      <strong>Agnosia = inability to recognize familiar stimuli despite intact sensory pathways, sensorium, and prior knowledge</strong>. Requires: (1) Intact sensory pathways, (2) Intact sensorium, (3) Previously knew the stimulus, (4) Organic cerebral lesion.
    </div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-mem">Type</th><th class="th-mem">Deficit</th><th class="th-mem">What's Preserved</th><th class="th-mem">Lesion</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Apperceptive Visual Agnosia</strong></td>
            <td>Cannot perceive object as coherent whole (cannot see the forest for the trees)</td>
            <td>Can identify individual features (lines, angles, colors). Identifies by touch.</td>
            <td>Medial (color) + Lateral (shape) occipital cortex</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Associative Visual Agnosia</strong></td>
            <td>Cannot connect visual percept to semantic memory (name, use)</td>
            <td>Describes object, confuses with similar-shaped objects. Recognizes by TOUCH. ⭐</td>
            <td>Occipito-temporal gyri (bilateral)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Prosopagnosia</strong></td>
            <td>Cannot recognize FACES (familiar or new) ⭐</td>
            <td>Recognizes by VOICE immediately. Can describe facial features.</td>
            <td>Bilateral ventromedial occipitotemporal (inferior occipital / midfusiform gyri)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Balint Syndrome TRIAD</strong></td>
            <td>1. Optic ataxia (cannot reach object) · 2. Oculomotor apraxia · 3. Simultagnosia (focuses on one thing only)</td>
            <td>Can see individual objects</td>
            <td>Bilateral parieto-occipital (vascular border zones)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Auditory Agnosia — Pure Word Deafness</strong></td>
            <td>Cannot understand SPOKEN words</td>
            <td>Hears and recognizes non-verbal sounds</td>
            <td>Disconnection bilateral primary auditory cortex from Wernicke's</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Auditory Agnosia — Phonagnosia</strong></td>
            <td>Cannot recognize familiar VOICES</td>
            <td>Language comprehension intact</td>
            <td>Temporal (uni/bilateral); right parietal for familiar voices</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Astereognosia</strong></td>
            <td>Cannot identify objects by TOUCH</td>
            <td>Vision intact</td>
            <td>Postcentral gyrus (parietal)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Asomatognosia</strong></td>
            <td>Unaware of own body parts + R-L disorientation (Gerstmann Syndrome)</td>
            <td>Motor strength intact</td>
            <td>Left angular gyrus (posterior perisylvian)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Anosognosia</strong></td>
            <td>Denial of neurologic deficit (e.g., denies hemiplegia)</td>
            <td>—</td>
            <td>Often right parietal</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--mem)">Apraxia ⭐</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-mem">Type</th><th class="th-mem">Deficit</th><th class="th-mem">Preserved</th><th class="th-mem">Lesion</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Ideomotor Apraxia</strong> (more common)</td><td>Cannot execute on VERBAL COMMAND; cannot gesture/pantomime on command</td><td>Spontaneous gestures; one-step tasks in context</td><td>Dominant anterior-inferior parietal (parietal); Callosal (anterior CC); Sympathetic (left premotor)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Ideational Apraxia</strong></td><td>Cannot SEQUENCE multi-step tasks (e.g., mailing a letter)</td><td>Individual steps can be done</td><td>Dominant temporo-parieto-occipital</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-info"><strong>Testing Sequence:</strong> Give verbal command → ask to mimic → demonstrate and ask to identify. Apraxia ≠ Agnosia: patient CAN recognize the object and knows how it's used, but cannot demonstrate the motor action on command.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--mem)">Aphasia ⭐⭐⭐</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr>
          <th class="th-mem">Type</th>
          <th class="th-mem">Fluent?</th>
          <th class="th-mem">Comprehend?</th>
          <th class="th-mem">Repeat?</th>
          <th class="th-mem">Naming</th>
          <th class="th-mem">Lesion</th>
        </tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Global</strong></td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="no">✗</td><td>Poor</td><td>Large perisylvian (Broca + Wernicke)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Mixed Transcortical</strong></td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td>Poor</td><td>Border zone MCA–ACA watershed</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Broca's</strong></td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="no">✗</td><td>Poor</td><td>Broca's area, anterior insula, frontal operculum</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Transcortical Motor</strong></td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td>Normal</td><td>Anterior/superior to Broca's</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Wernicke's</strong></td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="no">✗</td><td>Poor</td><td>Post. superior temporal gyrus / planum temporale</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Transcortical Sensory</strong></td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="no">✗</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td>Normal</td><td>Surrounding Wernicke's</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Conduction</strong></td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="no">✗</td><td>Poor</td><td>Posterior perisylvian (arcuate fasciculus)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Anomic</strong></td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td class="yes">✓</td><td>Poor</td><td>Inferior/anterior temporal lobe</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-mem"><strong>Key Pearl:</strong> Fluent + good comprehension + CANNOT repeat = Conduction aphasia (arcuate fasciculus). Transcortical aphasias PRESERVE repetition (isolated from Broca/Wernicke but watershed area connects them).</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--mem)">Cognitive Domains & Localization</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-mem">Location</th><th class="th-mem">Cognitive Symptoms</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Dominant (left) parietal lobe</td><td>Acalculia, agraphia, apraxia (Gerstmann syndrome)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Non-dominant (right) parietal / occipital</td><td>Visuospatial problems, neglect, hemispatial inattention</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Frontal lobe + connections</td><td>Behavioral: apathy, disinhibition, loss of empathy, perseveration, dietary changes → FTD</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Occipital lobe</td><td>Visual disturbances, visual processing (optic ataxia, simultagnosia)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Subcortical</td><td>Prominent cognitive SLOWING (can respond, just slow)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Extrapyramidal involvement</td><td>Parkinsonian features, hyperkinetic movements</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--mem)">Frontal Release Signs (Primitive Reflexes)</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-mem">Reflex</th><th class="th-mem">Stimulus</th><th class="th-mem">Response</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Grasp</strong></td><td>Palm stimulation</td><td>Inability to release grip</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Snout</strong></td><td>Tap on lips</td><td>Involuntary puckering</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Suck</strong></td><td>Object near mouth</td><td>Involuntary sucking</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Rooting</strong></td><td>Stroke cheek</td><td>Head turns toward stimulus</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-mem">Normal in infancy → suppressed by mature prefrontal cortex → REAPPEAR with frontal lobe lesions or dementia</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--mem)">Diagnostic Investigation Approach</div>
    <div class="flow flow-mem">
      <div class="flow-box" style="background:var(--mem);color:#fff;font-weight:700">Step 1: DETECT</div>
      <div class="flow-arr">↓</div>
      <div class="flow-box">History (timing, progression, baseline), collateral history from caregiver, medications, lifestyle, family history</div>
      <div class="flow-arr">↓</div>
      <div class="flow-box" style="background:var(--mem);color:#fff;font-weight:700">Step 2: ASSESS/DIFFERENTIATE</div>
      <div class="flow-arr">↓</div>
      <div class="flow-box">MMSE + MoCA · Blood tests (CBC, glucose, LFTs, TFTs, B12, folate, electrolytes, ESR/CRP) · Genotyping · Neurologic + physical exam</div>
      <div class="flow-arr">↓</div>
      <div class="flow-box" style="background:var(--mem);color:#fff;font-weight:700">Step 3: DIAGNOSE</div>
      <div class="flow-arr">↓</div>
      <div class="flow-box">⭐ <strong>First rule out REVERSIBLE causes</strong> (metabolic, infectious) · Structural MRI (mandatory for ALL dementia workup) · FDG-PET/SPECT · CSF (Aβ42, p-tau, t-tau for Alzheimer's) · Amyloid PET</div>
      <div class="flow-arr">↓</div>
      <div class="flow-box" style="background:var(--mem);color:#fff;font-weight:700">Step 4: TREAT</div>
      <div class="flow-arr">↓</div>
      <div class="flow-box">Symptomatic treatment · Lifestyle changes · Family dynamics & social support · Clinical trial registries</div>
    </div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-warn"><strong>MRI mandatory for ALL patients investigated for dementia</strong> — checks degeneration, vascular changes, atrophy, white matter changes, infarcts, microbleeds</div>
  </div>

</div><!-- end panel 2 -->

