<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

<div class="tab-panel" id="panel-3">

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Seizure vs Epilepsy Definitions</div>
    <div class="card-grid">
      <div class="hbox hbox-sz">
        <strong>Seizure</strong> = Transient occurrence of signs/symptoms due to abnormal excessive or synchronous neuronal activity. <em class="hl">Stereotyped</em> within same patient (seizure semiology). Variable between patients.
      </div>
      <div class="hbox hbox-info">
        <strong>Epilepsy (ILAE):</strong>
        (1) ≥2 unprovoked seizures &gt;24 hrs apart, OR<br>
        (2) 1 unprovoked seizure + ≥60% recurrence risk over 10 yrs, OR<br>
        (3) Diagnosis of an epilepsy syndrome
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">ILAE 2017 Classification of Seizures</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz" colspan="3">SEIZURE ONSET TYPE</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td style="vertical-align:top;background:var(--sz-light)"><strong>FOCAL ONSET</strong><br><span style="font-size:11px">One hemisphere; may have aware or impaired awareness</span></td>
            <td style="vertical-align:top;background:#fdf0ff"><strong>GENERALIZED ONSET</strong><br><span style="font-size:11px">Both hemispheres simultaneously</span></td>
            <td style="vertical-align:top"><strong>UNKNOWN ONSET</strong><br><span style="font-size:11px">Onset missed/obscured</span></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Generalized Motor Seizures ⭐</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz">Type</th><th class="th-sz">Definition</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Tonic-Clonic (Grand Mal) ⭐ Most Common</strong></td><td>Bilateral limb STIFFENING then rhythmic limb JERKING</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tonic</td><td>Bilateral limb ± neck stiffening or elevation</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Clonic</td><td>Begin, progress, and end with bilateral clonic jerking</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Myoclonic</td><td>Irregular, brief bilateral limb or whole-body jerks</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Myoclonic-Tonic-Clonic</td><td>Few myoclonic jerks → tonic-clonic</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Myoclonic-Atonic</td><td>Brief jerking of limbs/trunk → limb drop</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Atonic (Drop attacks)</td><td>Loss of tone of both limbs → recovery within seconds</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Epileptic Spasms</td><td>Sudden flexion or extension of proximal + truncal muscles</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="sub-title">Phases of Tonic-Clonic Seizure</div>
    <div class="stepper">
      <div class="step"><span class="sn">Hours before</span><span class="sv">Prodrome</span><span style="font-size:11px">Irritability, anxiety</span></div>
      <div class="step"><span class="sn">Seconds–minutes</span><span class="sv">Aura</span><span style="font-size:11px">Sensory: smell, sound, déjà vu</span></div>
      <div class="step" style="background:var(--sz-light)"><span class="sn">Ictal</span><span class="sv">Tonic Phase</span><span style="font-size:11px">Stiffening, LOC, opisthotonus, epileptic cry, cyanosis</span></div>
      <div class="step" style="background:var(--sz-light)"><span class="sn">Ictal</span><span class="sv">Clonic Phase</span><span style="font-size:11px">Rhythmic jerking, frothing, eye blinking</span></div>
      <div class="step"><span class="sn">Post-ictal</span><span class="sv">Terminal</span><span style="font-size:11px">Motionless, confused, agitated, then apparently normal</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Absence Seizures (Non-motor Generalized) ⭐</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz">Type</th><th class="th-sz">Key Features</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Typical Absence</strong></td>
            <td>Sudden brief cessation of activity + awareness · Rapid onset & offset · NO postictal confusion · +/− minor automatisms · <em class="hl">3/sec spike-wave EEG ⭐</em> · Age: 4–8yr (CAE) · Provoked by hyperventilation</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Atypical Absence</strong></td>
            <td>Change in tone (more pronounced) · Slower onset/cessation · Slow spike-wave EEG · No apparent LOC</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Myoclonic Absence</strong></td>
            <td>Absence + rhythmic 3/sec myoclonic movements</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Eyelid Myoclonia</strong></td>
            <td>Myoclonic eyelid jerks + upward gaze deviation on eye closure · Photosensitive</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-sz"><strong>Key criteria of absence seizure:</strong> Rapid onset · 3/sec spike-and-wave EEG · Complete loss of awareness · To an onlooker: "daydreaming" or "absentmindedness"</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Focal Seizures — Localization ⭐⭐</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz">Clinical Feature</th><th class="th-sz">Localization</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Jacksonian march (focal motor)</td><td>Prerolandic gyrus (primary motor cortex)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Masticatory automatisms, salivation, speech arrest</td><td>Amygdaloid nuclei / Opercular</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Simple contraversive (head/eye turning)</td><td>Frontal lobe</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Head/eye turning + arm movement + athetoid posture</td><td>Supplementary motor cortex</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Somatosensory aura</td><td>Contralateral postrolandic</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Unformed images, lights, patterns</td><td>Occipital lobe</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Auditory aura</td><td>Heschl gyri (superior temporal)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Vertiginous sensation</td><td>Superior temporal gyrus</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Olfactory aura ⭐</strong></td><td>Mesial temporal</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Gustatory aura</td><td>Insula</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Autonomic (palpitations, flushing)</td><td>Insular-orbital-frontal cortex</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Formed hallucinations, déjà vu, fear, automatisms ⭐</td><td>Temporal lobe (amygdaloid-hippocampal complex)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Staring</td><td>Frontal cortex / Amygdaloid-hippocampal / Reticular</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Gelastic seizure (laughing)</td><td>Hypothalamic hamartoma / Frontal</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-sz"><strong>Temporal lobe seizure pattern:</strong> Olfactory aura → fear → staring + lip-smacking automatisms → postictal confusion. Classic!</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Common Primary Generalized Epilepsy Syndromes ⭐⭐</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr>
          <th class="th-sz">Feature</th>
          <th class="th-sz">CAE (Childhood Absence)</th>
          <th class="th-sz">JAE (Juvenile Absence)</th>
          <th class="th-sz">JME (Juvenile Myoclonic) ⭐</th>
          <th class="th-sz">GTCS on Awakening</th>
        </tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Age of Onset</strong></td><td>4–8 yrs</td><td>10–15 yrs</td><td>15–20 yrs</td><td>10–25 yrs</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Seizure type</strong></td><td>Frequent brief absences</td><td>Frequent absences (less than CAE)</td><td>GTCS + absences + <em class="hl">morning myoclonus</em></td><td>GTCS, sometimes myoclonus</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>EEG</strong></td><td><em class="hl">3/sec spike-wave</em></td><td>Poly-spike and wave</td><td>Poly-spike and wave + photosensitivity</td><td>Spike-wave on waking + sleep onset</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Treatment</strong></td><td>Ethosuximide · Valproate · Levetiracetam</td><td colspan="3">Sodium Valproate · Levetiracetam</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Prognosis</strong></td><td>80% remit in adulthood; 40% develop GTCS</td><td>80% develop GTC; 80% seizure-free in adulthood</td><td>90% remit with AEDs but <em class="hl">RELAPSE if stopped ⭐</em></td><td>65% controlled; relapse off treatment</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Causes of Seizures by Age ⭐⭐</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz">Age Group</th><th class="th-sz">Most Common Causes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Neonates (&lt;1 mo)</strong></td><td>Perinatal hypoxia/ischemia · Intracranial hemorrhage · CNS infection · Metabolic (hypoglycemia, hypocalcemia, hypomagnesemia, pyridoxine deficiency) · Drug withdrawal · Developmental/genetic</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Infants &amp; Children (&lt;12 yr)</strong></td><td>Febrile seizures · Genetic disorders · CNS infection · Developmental · Trauma</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Adolescents (12–18 yr)</strong></td><td>Trauma · Genetic disorders · Infection · Illicit drug use · Brain tumor · Autoantibodies</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Young Adults (18–35 yr)</strong></td><td>Trauma · Alcohol withdrawal · Illicit drug use · Brain tumor · Autoantibodies</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Older Adults (&gt;35 yr) ⭐</strong></td><td><em class="hl">Cerebrovascular disease (STROKE)</em> · Brain tumor · Alcohol withdrawal · Metabolic disorders (uremia, hepatic failure, electrolyte abnormalities, hyperglycemia, hypoglycemia) · Alzheimer's/CNS degeneration · Autoantibodies</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-sz"><strong>⭐ Trauma is common in ALL age groups. New-onset seizure in elderly = cerebrovascular disease until proven otherwise.</strong></div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Stigmata of Neurocutaneous Syndromes</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz">Syndrome</th><th class="th-sz">Skin Finding</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Neurofibromatosis Type 1</strong></td><td>Café-au-lait spots · Neurofibromas · Plexiform neurofibromas · Lisch nodules (iris)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Tuberous Sclerosis</strong></td><td>Ash-leaf spots (hypopigmented) · Angiofibromas (facial) · Ungual fibromas · Shagreen patch</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Sturge-Weber Syndrome</strong></td><td>Port-wine stain (capillary hemangioma) on face — unilateral V1 distribution</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="sub-title">Examination Clues for Epilepsy</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz">Finding</th><th class="th-sz">Implication</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Hemiatrophy (limb/body asymmetry)</td><td>Perinatal cerebral insult</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Tongue bite marks (lateral borders)</td><td>Generalized tonic-clonic seizure</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Gingival hyperplasia</td><td>Phenytoin use ⭐</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dupuytren's contractures</td><td>Chronic barbiturate use</td></tr>
          <tr><td>End-gaze nystagmus + diplopia + poor tandem walk</td><td>AED toxicity (carbamazepine, phenytoin, lamotrigine)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-title" style="color:var(--sz)">Metabolic Causes of Seizures — Workup</div>
    <div class="hbox hbox-sz"><strong>Most common metabolic cause: Hyper- or Hypo-natremia ⭐</strong> (sometimes hyper/hypocalcemia)</div>
    <div class="sub-title">Common Antiepileptic Drugs</div>
    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th class="th-sz">Drug</th><th class="th-sz">Indications</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Valproic Acid</td><td>GTC · Focal · Absence · Myoclonic (broad spectrum)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Phenytoin</td><td>GTC · Focal · (NOT absence-1st line)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Carbamazepine</td><td>GTC · Focal</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Ethosuximide</td><td>Absence ONLY ⭐</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Lamotrigine</td><td>Generalized · Focal</td></tr>
