<!-- Q1 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🌀 DIZZINESS</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">1. A 60-year-old man presents with sudden continuous vertigo, diplopia, and difficulty walking. On exam: vertical nystagmus, normal head impulse test, skew deviation present. The MOST appropriate next step is:</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 2)">
    <li>A. Dix-Hallpike maneuver and Epley if positive</li>
    <li>B. Discharge with antihistamines for vestibular neuritis</li>
    <li>C. Emergency MRI — ADMIT for central vertigo workup</li>
    <li>D. Order CT angiography in the emergency department</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: C. HINTS = normal HI + vertical N + skew deviation → 100% central etiology. Admit immediately. Vertical nystagmus + diplopia = central red flags. CT has only 16% sensitivity for stroke. Avoid CTA in ED routinely. MRI is preferred.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q2 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🌀 DIZZINESS</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">2. A 52-year-old woman gets brief spinning dizziness every time she turns her head to the right in bed, lasting about 20 seconds, resolving on its own. No hearing loss. Dix-Hallpike (right side): torsional upbeating nystagmus after 5-second delay, fatigable. What is the treatment?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 0)">
    <li>A. Epley maneuver</li>
    <li>B. Vestibular suppressants for 2 weeks</li>
    <li>C. Urgent MRI brain</li>
    <li>D. Betahistine 96 mg TID</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: A. Classic BPPV: positional, brief, torsional + upbeating nystagmus with 5–40 sec latency, fatigable, reproducible. Treat with Epley maneuver. Vestibular suppressants should be max 3 days and not first-line for BPPV.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q3 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🌀 DIZZINESS</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">3. Which vertigo etiology best matches: episodic vertigo lasting several hours, accompanied by fluctuating hearing loss, tinnitus, and a sensation of ear fullness?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 2)">
    <li>A. BPPV</li>
    <li>B. Vertebrobasilar insufficiency</li>
    <li>C. Ménière's disease</li>
    <li>D. Vestibular neuritis</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: C. Ménière's disease = episodic vertigo (hours, up to 7), fluctuating hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness (ear "plugged"). Caused by excess endolymph. VBI = minutes. BPPV = seconds. Neuritis = days (continuous).</div>
</div>

<!-- Q4 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🤕 HEADACHE</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">4. A 45-year-old presents with sudden "worst headache of his life" reaching maximum intensity in 30 seconds. Non-contrast CT shows subarachnoid blood. CT angiography shows no aneurysm. What is the MOST appropriate next step?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 1)">
    <li>A. Diagnose as primary thunderclap headache and discharge</li>
    <li>B. Suspect angiogram-negative SAH and repeat vascular imaging</li>
    <li>C. Start triptans — this is likely a complicated migraine</li>
    <li>D. Discharge with NSAIDs as CT confirmed no active bleeding</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: B. CT-confirmed SAH must be treated as secondary HA. Angiogram-negative SAH occurs due to: small aneurysm not visualized, vasospasm, thrombosed aneurysm, or perimesencephalic non-aneurysmal SAH. Repeat vascular imaging required.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q5 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🤕 HEADACHE</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">5. A 26-year-old woman with known migraines develops unilateral right arm weakness during her headache which resolves in 48 hours. MRI is normal. She has a sister with similar episodes. What is the most likely diagnosis?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 1)">
    <li>A. TIA — refer to stroke unit urgently</li>
    <li>B. Familial Hemiplegic Migraine</li>
    <li>C. Sporadic Hemiplegic Migraine</li>
    <li>D. Migraine with brainstem aura</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: B. Hemiplegic migraine = migraine with motor weakness aura resolving &lt;72 hrs. MRI normal. Familial = at least 1 first-degree relative with similar attacks (her sister). Chromosomes 1, 2, 19. Channelopathy (CACNA1a, ATP1A2, SCN1A).</div>
</div>

<!-- Q6 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🤕 HEADACHE</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">6. A 35-year-old man is awakened from sleep by severe right orbital pain with right-sided lacrimation, nasal congestion, and ptosis. He paces around the room, unable to lie still. Duration: ~60 minutes. What is the FIRST-LINE acute treatment?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 0)">
    <li>A. 100% Oxygen at 10–12 L/min for 15–20 minutes</li>
    <li>B. Oral sumatriptan 100 mg</li>
    <li>C. Ibuprofen 800 mg PO</li>
    <li>D. Diazepam 5 mg IV</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: A. Cluster HA = severe unilateral orbital pain, ipsilateral autonomic features, restless patient. First-line: 100% O₂ 10–12 L/min × 15–20 min. Oral sumatriptan is NOT effective in cluster HA! Subcutaneous sumatriptan 6 mg is the pharmacologic option.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q7 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🧠 MEMORY & COGNITION</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">7. During Serial 7s testing, a patient gives the following responses: 100 → 93 → 86 → 78 → 71 → 64. What is the score?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 2)">
    <li>A. 5/5</li>
    <li>B. 4/5</li>
    <li>C. 3/5</li>
    <li>D. 2/5</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: C (4/5 per the standard but this specific example — score each correct SUBTRACTION). 100→93 (✓7), 93→86 (✓7), 86→78 (✗8), 78→71 (✓7), 71→64 (✓7) = 4/5. The error at 86→78 doesn't propagate. But in the trans example with 100,92,85,78,71,64: 92(✗8),85(✓7),78(✓7),71(✓7),64(✓7) = 4/5.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q8 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🧠 MEMORY & COGNITION</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">8. A post-stroke patient can clearly see a comb, describe "thin parallel lines," but cannot name it or demonstrate its use visually. When allowed to touch it, he immediately recognizes it and demonstrates combing. What is the diagnosis?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 1)">
    <li>A. Apperceptive visual agnosia</li>
    <li>B. Associative visual agnosia</li>
    <li>C. Ideomotor apraxia</li>
    <li>D. Prosopagnosia</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: B. Associative visual agnosia: patient can perceive the object's features (parallel lines) but CANNOT connect the visual percept to its semantic meaning (name, use). Recognizes by TOUCH. In apperceptive, patient cannot even perceive the whole object coherently. In ideomotor apraxia, patient can name/recognize the object but cannot demonstrate use ON COMMAND.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q9 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🧠 MEMORY & COGNITION</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">9. A patient has fluent speech with intact comprehension but CANNOT repeat sentences. She produces paraphasic errors. What aphasia type is this, and where is the lesion?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 1)">
    <li>A. Broca's aphasia — Broca's area</li>
    <li>B. Conduction aphasia — arcuate fasciculus</li>
    <li>C. Wernicke's aphasia — superior temporal gyrus</li>
    <li>D. Transcortical sensory aphasia — surrounding Wernicke's</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: B. Conduction aphasia = Fluent ✓, Comprehension ✓, Repetition ✗. Lesion = posterior perisylvian region, specifically the arcuate fasciculus. Broca's: non-fluent, comprehension ok, no repetition. Wernicke's: fluent, no comprehension, no repetition. Transcortical Sensory: fluent, no comprehension, INTACT repetition.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q10 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">⚡ SEIZURES</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">10. A 7-year-old girl is noted by her teacher to have multiple daily episodes of "blank staring" lasting 5–10 seconds each, resuming activity immediately without confusion. EEG shows 3/sec spike-and-wave. What is the expected prognosis?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 0)">
    <li>A. 80% remit in adulthood; 40% will develop GTC</li>
    <li>B. 90% remit but relapse if AEDs withdrawn</li>
    <li>C. Lifelong treatment required in all cases</li>
    <li>D. 80% develop GTC and 80% seizure-free in adulthood</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: A. Childhood Absence Epilepsy (CAE): age 4–8, frequent brief absences, 3/sec spike-wave EEG. Prognosis: 80% remit in adulthood, but 40% will eventually develop GTCS. Treatment: Ethosuximide, Valproate, or Levetiracetam.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q11 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">⚡ SEIZURES</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">11. A 17-year-old boy presents with episodes of arm jerking every morning when he wakes up, causing him to drop his toothbrush. He had one generalized convulsion last month upon awakening. EEG: poly-spike-and-wave + photosensitivity. Which drug should be AVOIDED in this patient?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 2)">
    <li>A. Valproic acid</li>
    <li>B. Levetiracetam</li>
    <li>C. Carbamazepine</li>
    <li>D. Lamotrigine</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: C. This is Juvenile Myoclonic Epilepsy (JME) — morning myoclonus + GTCS on awakening + polyspike EEG with photosensitivity. Carbamazepine (and phenytoin) can WORSEN absence and myoclonic seizures. First-line: Valproate or Levetiracetam. JME requires lifelong therapy — relapse if stopped.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q12 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">⚡ SEIZURES</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">12. A 24-year-old woman describes episodes preceded by a "strange burning smell" followed by intense fear, then staring with lip-smacking. She is confused for 2–3 minutes afterward. What is the most likely seizure localization?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 3)">
    <li>A. Occipital lobe</li>
    <li>B. Frontal lobe supplementary motor area</li>
    <li>C. Parietal somatosensory cortex</li>
    <li>D. Temporal lobe (mesial — amygdaloid-hippocampal complex)</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: D. Classic temporal lobe seizure: Olfactory aura (mesial temporal) → emotional aura (fear) → automatisms (lip-smacking) → postictal confusion. The amygdaloid-hippocampal complex generates olfactory aura, fear, and memory-related phenomena (déjà vu).</div>
</div>

<!-- Q13 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🌀 DIZZINESS + ⚡ INTEGRATION</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">13. Which of the following antiepileptic drugs is associated with gingival hyperplasia?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 1)">
    <li>A. Carbamazepine</li>
    <li>B. Phenytoin</li>
    <li>C. Valproic acid</li>
    <li>D. Ethosuximide</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: B. Phenytoin → gingival hyperplasia. Carbamazepine → end-gaze nystagmus, diplopia, ataxia (toxicity signs). Barbiturates → Dupuytren's contractures. These are important physical exam clues in epilepsy patients.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q14 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🧠 MEMORY & COGNITION</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">14. A 75-year-old man cannot recognize his granddaughter's face when she visits but immediately knows who she is when she speaks. He can describe her facial features accurately. Lesion localization?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 0)">
    <li>A. Bilateral ventromedial occipitotemporal (inferior occipital / midfusiform gyri)</li>
    <li>B. Left Broca's area</li>
    <li>C. Right parietal lobe</li>
    <li>D. Left angular gyrus</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="mcq-exp">Correct: A. Prosopagnosia = inability to recognize faces despite intact visual acuity and ability to perceive features. Recognizes by voice. Associated with bilateral ventromedial occipitotemporal lesions including inferior occipital/midfusiform gyri. Can also have difficulty identifying own car among others.</div>
</div>

<!-- Q15 -->
<div class="mcq-item">
  <div class="mcq-tag">🤕 HEADACHE</div>
  <div class="mcq-q">15. Which of the following correctly matches the headache type to its most distinguishing feature?</div>
  <ul class="mcq-opts" onclick="handleMCQ(event, this, 2)">
    <li>A. Tension HA — WORSENED by physical activity</li>
    <li>B. Cluster HA — Bilateral, band-like, pericranial tenderness</li>
    <li>C. Cluster HA — Patient is restless/pacing + ipsilateral autonomic features</li>
    <li>D. Migraine — Exclusively nocturnal, wakes from sleep</li>
